            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7288.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">J. E. Smith 1824–36</ref>, <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3819.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">W. J. Hooker 1830b</ref>, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4756.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Lightfoot 1777</ref> were standard reference works on the British flora.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4418.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Koch 1843–4</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1996.xml" resp="#automat">letter from C. C. Babington, 22 November 1856</ref>, n. 2.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2009.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from George Dickie, 1 December 1856</ref>. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1316.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Dickie</ref> was professor of natural history at Belfast University, but was particularly noted for his botanical studies of the area around Aberdeen, his birthplace (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1983.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">R. Desmond 1977</ref>).</note>
